body:
Similar to my previous issue https://github.com/llvm/circt/issues/5531, several canonicalizations drop attributes (except `sv.namehint`). While I agree that it is unsafe to propagate discardable attributes freely, I think that the current implementation might be slightly to conservative.
As @teqdruid pointed out in https://github.com/llvm/circt/pull/5532#discussion_r1251266106:
> In general, dialect attributes should be propagated best effort, so I think it's appropriate to propagated them through the canonicalizers where it's obvious what the destination/source op is.

IMHO one such example would be when the canonicalization rewrites the operation without changing the dialect operation class.
Here is an example for the canonicalize pattern [`extract(olo, extract(ilo, x)) = extract(olo + ilo, x)`](https://github.com/llvm/circt/blob/c4038382fbbaea7b7b1abebaf4ba769d51609b11/lib/Dialect/Comb/CombFolds.cpp#L632):
```
module {
  hw.module @attrsGone(in %arg0: i64, out res: i32) {
    %0 = comb.extract %arg0 from 0 : (i64) -> i42
    %1 = comb.extract %0 from 0 {custom_dialect.attr = "test"} : (i42) -> i32
    hw.output %1 : i32
  }
}
```
Current result after `-canonicalize`:
```
module {
  hw.module @attrsGone(in %arg0 : i64, out res : i32) {
    %0 = comb.extract %arg0 from 0 : (i64) -> i32
    hw.output %0 : i32
  }
}
```
With a best effort propagation:
```
module {
  hw.module @attrsGone(in %arg0 : i64, out res : i32) {
    %0 = comb.extract %arg0 from 0 {custom_dialect.attr = "test"} : (i64) -> i32
    hw.output %0 : i32
  }
}
```
